# arvo-narrow. Design

The concrete narrowing layer. Hosts every `impl const Narrow<T>` for
the primitive pairs that arvo cares about. Per round 202604271346
Q-C, this lives downstream of `arvo-bitmask` (because it uses concrete
mask types). The `Narrow<T>` trait declaration lives in
`arvo-bits-contracts` (merged in from the previously-separate
`arvo-narrow-contracts` crate during round 202604280034).
`#![no_std]`, no alloc.

Depends on `notko`, `arvo-storage`, `arvo-bits-contracts`,
`arvo-mask-contracts`, `arvo-bitmask`.

## Concrete impls

Pass B.4 of round 202604281000 populates the impl tables. Two
families ship:

**Per-source-target primitive narrowing.** Cross-primitive narrowing
between `u8`, `u16`, `u32`, `u64`, `u128` (and signed counterparts).
Each pair where the source is wider than the target gets an impl
that masks the high bits and casts down. Pattern:

```rust
impl const Narrow<u8> for u16 {
    fn narrow_to<const N: u16>(self) -> u8 {
        let mask = Mask64::mask_for_width(USize(N as usize));
        ((self as u64) & mask.to_raw()) as u8
    }

    fn narrow_to_unmasked<const N: u16>(self) -> u8 {
        self as u8
    }
}
```

The signed-source variants narrow with sign-preserving masks where
the target is also signed; sign-source-to-unsigned-target uses the
unmasked path's `as` cast (Rust's `as` on signed-to-unsigned takes
the bit pattern). Each pair documents the sign-handling at the
impl site.

**Typed `Bits<M, S, Sign> -> Bits<N, S, Sign>` narrowing for M > N.**
Same strategy, same sign, narrower destination. The impl body
forwards through the underlying primitive narrow:

```rust
impl<const M: u16, const N: u16, S: Strategy, Sign: Signedness>
    const Narrow<Bits<N, S, Sign>> for Bits<M, S, Sign>
where
    S: BitsContainerFor<M, Sign> + BitsContainerFor<N, Sign>,
    /* compile-time guard: M > N */
{
    fn narrow_to<const W: u16>(self) -> Bits<N, S, Sign> {
        let raw = self.to_raw();
        Bits::from_raw(raw.narrow_to::<W>())
    }
}
```

Cross-strategy narrowing (M > N with different S1 / S2) is out of
scope; consumers cast strategy first via `Conversion`, then narrow.

The empty-crate lint clears once these impls land.

## Why this lives downstream

`Narrow` impls need concrete masks. `Mask64` is in `arvo-bitmask`.
`Bits<N, S>` is in `arvo-storage`. The narrow contract surface
(`arvo-narrow-contracts`) names neither concretely; only when the impl
body is written does the dependency materialise.

Keeping `Narrow` impls in their own crate lets generic-over-narrow
consumers (the bitfield macro, the algorithm crates) bind only to
`arvo-narrow-contracts` without pulling in mask concretes. The `arvo`
facade pulls this crate to expose the common impls; consumers that
only need the trait surface get a smaller transitive footprint.

